  "prompt": "Can God make a boulder so heavy he can't lift it?",
  "response": "The question \"Can God make a boulder so heavy that he can't lift it?\" is a classic example of a paradox often used in discussions of omnipotence. It poses a contradiction in terms, challenging the logical consistency of the concept of an all-powerful being. If God can create such a boulder, then there is something he cannot do (lift it), which would imply that he is not omnipotent. Conversely, if God cannot create such a boulder, then there is something he cannot do (create the boulder), which also challenges the notion of omnipotence.\n\nThis paradox highlights the limitations of human language and logic when applied to divine attributes. Some theologians argue that omnipotence does not imply the ability to do the logically impossible. Others might suggest that God's omnipotence is compatible with his nature, meaning he cannot perform actions that are intrinsically contradictory.\n\nUltimately, the resolution to this paradox depends on one's interpretation of omnipotence and the nature of God, which varies across different religious and philosophical perspectives.",
